I wasn't familiar w Papert's work, but the history of ideas is an interconnected set of influences that's hard to isolate to individual moments or people. It's stories all the way down, & it all depends on your reference frame for where to begin. Thanks for resetting my origin.

This week's Investment Round includes new funding for @UiPath , @dianomi , @whoop , @3radicalTweets , @virtualiticsVR and more http:// mobilemarketingmagazine.com/investment-rou nd-uipath-dianomi-whoop-edgybees-3radical-virtualitics …

I'll listen to your podcast later. Live interaction with models isn't really new right? That was already an important part of Seymour Papert's work. Real time bodily interaction is new though, which may help us form intuitions for these kinds of complex systems.

It may have an embodied component, although I think that interaction is more important in this. I referred to an easier advantage of VR data visualization: visualizing sets that are just too big for a screen requiring all the space you can get.

I also think that there will be tools like toplogical data analysis that use the geometry of data + color in order to intuitively grok higher dimensional relationships. See more with Gunnar Carlsson's work.

Standing in the midst of data does invoke the principles of embodied cognition. Chris North also says that live interaction of manipulating variables in real-time is also a unique affordance of VR for data visualization: http:// voicesofvr.com/375-immersive- analytics-embodied-cognition/ …

While the visualization is certainly appealing, incorporating AI is the interesting part for me. The shelf life of data is short - it needs to be analyzed quickly, and you need help noticing anomalies. Otherwise, it will only help in knowing why you missed opportunities.
Agreed! That’s the future key imo (1) how to create the data, especially for non-techies and (2) how to interpret it.

Certainly buzzword compliant (just needs blockchain in there somewhere), but if it makes data relevant and digestible in real time, it's huge. Data analysis feels too much like math for many, regardless the value.
